14 WHEREAS, Decatur County Schools reported a chronic absenteeism rate of 38.1 percent in
15 the 2023-2024 school year, a sharp increase from 22.1 percent in the 2018-2019 school year;
16 and
17 WHEREAS, absenteeism can be attributed to a variety of factors, including, but not limited
18 to, health issues, family instability, socioeconomic barriers, transportation difficulties, and
19 school climate concerns; and
20 WHEREAS, addressing chronic absenteeism requires a collaborative and multifaceted
21 approach that involves school administrators, educators, parents, policymakers, and
22 community organizations; and
23 WHEREAS, research has shown that early intervention and targeted support programs can
24 significantly reduce chronic absenteeism and its negative effects; and
25 WHEREAS, in December, 2024, the Department of Education demonstrated its commitment
26 to addressing this issue by hosting a summit which was attended by representatives from
27 multiple state agencies, education organizations, and local school systems in an effort to raise
28 awareness and develop collaborative solutions; and
29 WHEREAS, a comprehensive review of student attendance in pre-kindergarten through
30 grade 12 education is needed for legislators, education leaders, and community stakeholders
31 to examine the root causes of chronic absenteeism, evaluate best practices for improving
32 student attendance and engagement, and recommend legislative and policy initiatives to
33 improve student attendance and engagement.
- 2 -

